## Context

This is round 12 of a Codex chain on the M-PANELS gmsh meshing pipeline. The chain is closing a class of bugs where filesystem/backend faults were misclassified as 4xx geometry-rejection rather than 5xx backend faults.

R11 returned CHANGES_REQUIRED with three P2 findings. Two were applied verbatim. One was rejected with rationale — please confirm or push back.

## R11 #2 APPLIED (to_foam.py:165)

Broadened `except FileNotFoundError` after `_make_tarball()` to also catch `OSError` (PermissionError, ENOSPC, EIO). Verbatim per R11 suggested fix.

## R11 #3 APPLIED (to_foam.py:243-260)

Wrapped the host-side polyMesh materialization block (parent.mkdir + container.get_archive + _extract_tarball) in `except (OSError, tarfile.TarError)`. Verbatim per R11 suggested fix.

## R11 #1 REJECTED (gmsh_runner.py:139)

R11 #1 suggested wrapping `gmsh.merge(str(stl_path))` in its own try/except so plain-Exception failures relabel as `OSError` when `stl_path.exists()` is True (catching EACCES on a permission-denied mount).

REJECTED on review because:

1. This conflicts with the R2/R3 architectural contract encoded in `test_gmsh_runner_normalizes_raw_binding_exception` (line 151 of `ui/backend/tests/test_meshing_gmsh.py`). That test was the explicit outcome of R2 P1 / R3 P1 review and documents:
   > "gmsh's Python bindings raise plain Exception on geometry-level failures (merge / classify / generate). Those must be wrapped INSIDE gmsh_runner as GmshMeshGenerationError so the pipeline maps them to gmsh_diverged."

2. Real `OSError` from the underlying STL read is already caught by the explicit `except OSError: raise` boundary in `_gmsh_inline` (gmsh_runner.py line 218 area). Only gmsh-binding-wrapped re-raises reach the catch-all. Those are dominantly geometry-side ("STL has malformed header", "non-watertight surface") — the canonical 4xx case the route layer expects.

3. The "EACCES on a permission-denied mount surfaced as plain Exception from gmsh.merge" scenario R11 #1 hypothesizes requires gmsh's C bindings to swallow the OS-level error and re-raise as plain Python Exception. This is not the documented gmsh API behavior and isn't observed in any of the project's failure logs.

4. Applying R11 #1 verbatim broke the R2/R3 test (commit reverted; see HEAD).

Inline NOTE block at `ui/backend/services/meshing_gmsh/gmsh_runner.py:138-152` (around `gmsh.merge`) documents the rejection rationale.

## Question for R12

Two questions:

(a) **R11 #1 rationale check**: Do you accept the R2/R3 contract argument? If yes: confirm the rejection. If no: explain why the R2/R3 contract should be flipped, and what evidence drives "host EACCES manifests as plain Exception from gmsh.merge" as the more likely interpretation than "malformed STL".

(b) **Remaining surfaces**: With R11 #2 and #3 applied, are there any further surfaces in `gmsh_runner.py`, `to_foam.py`, or `pipeline.py` where a backend/filesystem fault could escape as either:
   - a raw uncaught exception (5xx with no structured contract), or
   - a misclassified geometry rejection (4xx)?

## Verdict

Verdict ENUM: APPROVE / CHANGES_REQUIRED / INCONCLUSIVE.

If APPROVE: state so explicitly so the chain can close (chain has been running 12 rounds; R7 onward has been increasingly narrow disk-full / permission edge cases).

If CHANGES_REQUIRED: list each new finding with file:line, severity (P1/P2/P3), and verbatim suggested fix. Be terse.

If INCONCLUSIVE: explain what evidence is missing.

Under 600 words.
